{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17511223","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17511223"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T12:39:31+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T12:39:31+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11716"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"11716","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11716"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.25,0.23,0.37,0.01,0.13]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4331"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107969"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4331","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4331"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11716"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90382"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"30"},{"type":"tags","id":"31"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"316"},{"type":"tags","id":"623"},{"type":"tags","id":"1184"},{"type":"tags","id":"2097"},{"type":"tags","id":"2560"},{"type":"tags","id":"2589"},{"type":"tags","id":"2778"},{"type":"tags","id":"4875"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4977"},{"type":"tags","id":"4982"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"8869"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11626"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"5907"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6891"},{"type":"contributions","id":"36496"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107969","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/107969"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 65-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with a two week history of progressive weakness in his right arm. This has been impacting his fine motor movements and culminated this morning when he was unable to tie his shoe laces. He has worsening difficulty using his mobile phone. Over the last week he has also noticed slurring of his speech. Today when he was driving to the Emergency Department he experienced blurred vision and felt unsteady walking.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHis medical history includes chronic obstructive pulmonary disease with a mild obstructive ventilatory defect. He uses fluticasone/salmeterol puffer daily, and never uses salbutamol. He is an active smoker of 30 cigarettes per day and has smoked since he was 22 years old. He has no allergies.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHe has slurred speech with associated word finding difficulty. \u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHis facial sensation is intact bilaterally, and he has no nystagmus. \u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHe has right upper limb weakness in a pyramidal pattern without pronator drift. He has dense numbness of his right upper limb. His reflexes are symmetrical. He has marked incoordination of his right upper limb. \u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThere is no lower limb weakness or sensory change.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Pancoast tumour","Lambert Eaton syndrome","Brain metastases","Radial nerve compression","Motor neurone disease"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis is an older male smoker who presents with a subacute progressive neurological deficit (mainly right upper limb weakness, right upper limb sensory deficit, and isolated dysarthria without other cranial nerve deficits). Given his smoking history, \u003Cstrong\u003Emetastatic disease\u003C/strong\u003E from a bronchogenic neoplasm must be considered and excluded.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPancoast tumour\u003C/strong\u003E can cause weakness in the intrinsic muscles of the hand. It is also likely to cause a Horner\u0027s syndrome which is absent in this case. A Pancoast tumour would not explain his slurred speech.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELambert-Eaton syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E is associated with lung cancer but clinically mimics myasthenia gravis. Myasthenia gravis can cause slurred speech, but usually presents with bilateral proximal muscle weakness and bilateral ocular ptosis, which is not present in this case. Lambert-Eaton syndrome would not explain his sensory deficits.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERadial nerve compression\u003C/strong\u003E would explain his right upper limb weakness (particularly weakness of right wrist extension) and sensory deficits (particularly right hand dorsal surface). However, this would not explain his slurred speech.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMotor neurone disease\u003C/strong\u003E can present with asymmetrical weakness, and can have bulbar features such as dysarthria or dysphagia. Motor neurone disease usually has both upper motor neurone lesion and lower motor neurone lesion features on examination, e.g. wasting, fasciculations and hyper-reflexia, which are not present in this case. Motor neurone disease would not explain his sensory deficits.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ENeurological diseases can be easily characterised by the time course\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Eacute - usually vascular (like stroke), or electrical (like seizure)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Esubacute - often related to malignancy or compressive aetiologies\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Echronic - usually degenerative\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003ENote:  In this particular case, the patient later underwent a CT brain, which demonstrated multiple intracerebral metastases. He has metastases in his left motor cortex, left sensory cortex and bilateral cerebellum. There was associated oedema and midline shift. His CT chest showed a large lung mass and mediastinal lymphadenopathy, making metastatic lung cancer the most likely diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Neurological features that are difficult to localise can be secondary to multiple metastases"],"references":["Nasim F, Sabath BF, Eapen GA. Lung Cancer. Med Clin N Am 2019; 103:463-73. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/30955514/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90382"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11716"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90382","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/90382"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-05T14:33:13+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-05T14:33:13+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4331"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107969"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"7","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/7"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Neurology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"11","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec1","name":"Respiratory Medicine","synonyms":["Pulmonology"],"description":null,"position":nul